\begin_layout Section
Cutting Plane Methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Cutting-Plane-Methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this chapter is to present some polynomial-time algorithms for convex optimization.
 These algorithms use knowledge of the function in a minimal way,
 essentially by querying the function value along with weak bounds on its support and range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a continuously differentiable convex function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:first_order"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(y)\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),y-x\right\rangle \text{ for all }y.\label{eq:sub_grad_def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 be any minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)\geq f(x^{*})\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle .
\]

\end_inset

Therefore,
 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle \leq0$
\end_inset

.
 Namely,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 lies in a halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 with normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Roughly speaking,
 this shows that each gradient computation cuts the set of possible solutions in half.
 In one dimension,
 this allows us to do a binary search to minimize convex functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rn$
\end_inset

,
 binary search still works.
 In this chapter,
 we will cover several ways to do this binary search.
 All of them follow the same framework,
 called the 
\emph on
cutting plane method
\emph default
.
 In this method,
 the convex set or function of interest is given by an oracle,
 typically a 
\emph on
separation oracle
\emph default
 (for definitions in a broader context,
 see Defs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:SEP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:GRAD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in the next chapter):
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin K\subseteq\R^{n}$
\end_inset

,
 the oracle finds a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)^{\top}(y-x)\leq0\text{ for all }y\in K.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cutting plane methods address the following class of problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prob:abstract_convex_problem"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finding a point in a convex set
\end_layout

\end_inset

Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0,R>0,$
\end_inset

 and a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq R\cdot B^{n}$
\end_inset

 specified by a separation oracle,
 find a point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in K$
\end_inset

 or conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol K\leq\epsilon^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The complexity of an algorithm is measured by the number of calls to the oracle and the number of arithmetic operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
To minimize a convex function,
 we set 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 to be the set of (approximate) minimizers of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:vol2val"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we relate the problem of proving that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vol(K)$
\end_inset

 is small to the problem of finding an approximate minimizer of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this framework,
 we maintain a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 that contains the set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 In each iteration,
 we choose some 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 and query the oracle for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x^{(k)})$
\end_inset

 .
 The guarantee for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(.)$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 lies in the halfspace 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{(k)}=\{y:g(x^{(k)})^{\top}(y-x^{(k)})\leq0\}
\]

\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subset H^{(k)}\cap E^{(k)}.$
\end_inset

 The algorithm continues by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 to be a convex set that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{(k)}\cap E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

