\begin_layout Standard
We start by explaining the Ellipsoid method.
 The algorithm maintains an ellipsoid
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E^{(k)}\defeq\{y\in\Rn:\ (y-x^{(k)})^{\top}\left(A^{(k)}\right)^{-1}(y-x^{(k)})\leq1\}
\]

\end_inset

that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and becomes smaller in volume in each step.
 Note that for this to be an ellipsoid the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 must be symmetric PSD.
 After we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x^{(k)})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 via (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Hk"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 we define 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k+1)}$
\end_inset

 to be the smallest volume ellipsoid containing 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}\cap H^{(k)}$
\end_inset

.
 The key observation is that the volume of the ellipsoid 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 decreases by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\Theta(\frac{1}{n})$
\end_inset

 every iteration.
 This volume property holds for any halfspace through the center of the current ellipsoid (not only for the one whose normal is the gradient),
 a property we will exploit in the next chapter.
\end_layout

