 In general,
 knowing that the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 lies in a small volume set does not provide enough information to find a point with small function value.
 For example,
 if we only knew that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 lies in the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x:x_{1}=0\}$
\end_inset

,
 we would still need to search for 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 over an 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 dimensional space.
 However,
 if the set is constructed by the cutting plane framework (Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:cutting_plane"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 then we can guarantee that small volume implies that any point in the set has close to optimal function value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies that we can minimize any convex function with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 additive error in 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n^{2}\log(1/\varepsilon))$
\end_inset

 iterations.
 To make the statement more general,
 we note that the Ellipsoid method can be used for non-differentiable functions.
 In the next theorem,
 we allow for a general 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

progress
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function and an arbitrary support 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 The convergence argument works for any monotonic,
 scale-and-shift-invariant progress measure.
 To allow for non-differentiable convex functions,
 in place of gradient,
 we use the subgradient (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
